---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { CONTACT_EMAIL } from '../consts';

// NOTE FOR THE DEVELOPER (not shown on the page): this policy is written to be
// accurate and honest, but it is not legal advice. Before you rely on it for the
// App Store or for EU/UK traffic, have a real lawyer read it. See COMPLIANCE.md.

const title = 'Privacy Policy | Questling';
const description =
  'Questling has no accounts and no servers. Everything the app saves stays on your phone, and this site sets no cookies. Nothing personal is collected, tracked, sold, or shared.';

// The date the policy was last actually changed (not auto-updated).
const lastUpdated = 'July 6, 2026';
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container container--narrow">
      <h1>Privacy Policy</h1>
      <p class="updated">Last updated {lastUpdated}</p>

      <p class="lead">
        I'm the developer of Questling, and I built it so your family's stuff stays
        with your family. This policy covers two things: the Questling app on your
        phone, and this website at getquestling.com. Neither one collects personal
        information about you or your child. Here is exactly how each one works.
      </p>

      <h2>What the app keeps on your phone</h2>
      <p>
        The Questling app has no accounts, no login, and no servers behind it.
        Everything it saves lives only on your own device:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>your gems, the quests you've finished, and the quest you're on now</li>
        <li>the rewards you set up in the Shop</li>
        <li>any photos you add to the Memory Journal</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        I never see any of it. There is nowhere for the app to send it, so it doesn't.
        Because there is no server in the middle, nothing syncs between devices either.
      </p>

      <h2>Camera and photos</h2>
      <p>
        Questling asks for camera or photo access for one reason: so you can save a
        picture alongside a quest as a keepsake in the Memory Journal. Those photos
        stay on your phone and are never uploaded anywhere.
      </p>

      <h2>This website</h2>
      <p>
        The website you're reading is a set of static files served over Cloudflare's
        network. It has no backend, no database, and no accounts. The Contact page is
        just a mailto link that opens your own email app, so anything you send reaches
        me the way an ordinary email would. Two things are worth naming plainly:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Analytics.</strong> I use Cloudflare Web Analytics to see rough
          traffic, like how many people visited a page, which sites linked here, and
          which countries visitors came from. It is privacy-first and cookieless. It
          sets no cookies, stores nothing on your device, and builds no profile of you.
          The numbers are aggregate and cannot identify you.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Fonts.</strong> The site loads the Inter typeface from Google Fonts.
          To deliver the font, Google may receive your IP address as part of that
          request. That is standard for Google Fonts, and it is the only third-party
          resource this site loads.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        No cookies. No advertising trackers. No third-party analytics beyond the
        cookieless counting above.
      </p>

      <h2>Cookies and consent banners</h2>
      <p>
        You will not see a cookie-consent banner on this site, and that is on purpose.
        The site sets no cookies and stores nothing on your device, and the analytics I
        use is cookieless. Consent banners exist to cover cookies and similar tracking
        storage, so with none of that here, there is nothing to ask your permission for.
      </p>

      <h2>What I collect</h2>
      <p>
        To put it plainly: I do not collect any personal information about you or your
        child, from the app or from this website. The app keeps its data on your device
        and sends me nothing. The website's traffic numbers are aggregate and anonymous.
        I do not sell, rent, or share personal information, because I don't have any to
        begin with.
      </p>

      <h2>Children</h2>
      <p>
        Questling is made for a parent to run on their own phone. Children do not create
        accounts, do not log in, and do not use the app on a device of their own. Because
        nothing is collected from anyone, no personal information is ever gathered from a
        child. This is how I keep Questling in step with children's privacy rules like
        COPPA: the surest way to protect a kid's data is to never collect it. Questling is
        written and positioned for parents. If you're a parent with a question about any of
        this, please email me and I'll answer honestly.
      </p>

      <div class="callout">
        <span class="badge"><span class="badge__dot"></span>Coming soon</span>
        <h2>Subscriptions</h2>
        <p>
          Questling is free today. I'm planning to add an optional paid subscription,
          handled through Apple's in-app purchase system (likely using a service called
          RevenueCat to manage it). When that goes live:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            Apple processes the payment. I never see your card number or billing details.
          </li>
          <li>
            Apple and RevenueCat may handle a small amount of purchase and
            anonymous-identifier data needed to run the subscription, such as whether a
            purchase is currently active.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          This section is a placeholder, and none of it is active yet. When the
          subscription launches, I'll update this policy with the specifics and change the
          date at the top before it turns on.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2>Deleting your data</h2>
      <p>
        In the app, you can remove individual photos and rewards whenever you like. If you
        want everything gone at once, deleting the app takes all of it off your device with
        it. There is nothing stored anywhere else for me to delete, because there is nowhere
        else. On the website there is no account to close and nothing personal to erase.
      </p>

      <h2>Changes</h2>
      <p>
        If I change this policy, I'll update the "Last updated" date at the top. If a change
        is significant, like the subscription going live, I'll make the update clear rather
        than quiet.
      </p>

      <h2>Questions</h2>
      <p>
        Email me at <a href={`mailto:${CONTACT_EMAIL}`}>{CONTACT_EMAIL}</a>. A real person,
        me, reads it.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .container--narrow { max-width: 720px; }
  h1 { margin-bottom: 0.25rem; }
  .updated { color: var(--ink-soft); font-size: 0.95rem; margin-bottom: 2rem; }
  .lead { font-size: 1.15rem; color: var(--ink); margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
  h2 { font-size: 1.3rem; margin-top: 2.2rem; }
  p, li { color: var(--ink); }
  ul { margin: 0 0 1.1rem; padding-left: 1.3rem; }
  li { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
  a { color: var(--primary); text-decoration: underline; }

  /* The subscription notice is a full-bordered callout, not a live section, so it
     reads as "not active yet" at a glance. */
  .callout {
    margin-top: 2.4rem;
    padding: 1.4rem 1.6rem;
    background: var(--primary-tint);
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
  }
  .callout h2 { margin-top: 0.7rem; }
  .callout p:last-child { margin-bottom: 0; }
</style>
